data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The temporary escape hatch (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncOverAsync`) that you configured in .NET 10 **no longer exists**.

Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()` — and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime with no workaround.

## The fix

Convert all sync calls to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods become `async` and use `await`
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`

This is async all the way up, so callers must also be updated to `await` these methods — propagate `async` through your call chain up to the controller/endpoint level.
